    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1930-01-08T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1930-01-08T04:00:00-05:00" n="441"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d441">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">793.003/249: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Perkins</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Peiping</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1930-01-08T17:00:00+08:00"
                            >January 8, 1930—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 5:40 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>26. Legation’s No. 7, January 2, 6 p.m. Japanese Chargé d’Affaires said to me
                    today that it was not the intention of his Government to make a protest with
                    regard to the Chinese Government’s mandate of December 28. In view of the
                    Sino-Japanese exchange of notes of April 26–27 last<note n="47"
                        xml:id="d441fn47">For texts of notes signed at Nanking, see <hi
                            rend="italic">The China Yearbook</hi>, 1929–30, pp. 837–839.</note>
                    which he referred to as a <hi rend="italic">modus vivendi</hi>, the Japanese
                    Government considers that China has agreed, pending treaty revision between the
                    two countries, to make no attempt to exercise jurisdiction over Japanese
                    nationals and that therefore it is unnecessary for Japan to take any action in
                    the present circumstances. See Legation’s mail despatch No. 279 [<hi
                        rend="italic">2079</hi>], May 4, 1929.<note n="48" xml:id="d441fn48">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Perkins</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
